something worth noticing when using R:
* in a dataframe, the c(some strings) function as an arguement will create a factor instead of a vector.
* if we don't specify the levels of a factor, R will arrange the levels alphabatically.

the result of  ` as_incidence_matrix(net2)  %*%  t(as_incidence_matrix(net2)) ` is the counting that how many Users that these two S share.

so, we can derive a conclusion that, it we use an incidence matrix to represent a undirected simiple graph, and we can derive a conresponding adjacency matrix by multiplying the network matrix by its transposed matrix.

and look at the following code to understand why the incidence matrix is somewaht called the **two-mode matrix**

```
net2.bp <- bipartite.projection(net2)

# look at the condistion expression at the end of the statement
# !is.na(...) gives the label of the media who ha a non-NA value on the attribute media.type
# so these statement plot the co=membership relation bettter the media
plot(net2.bp$proj1, vertex.label.color="black", vertex.label.dist=1,

     vertex.size=7, vertex.label=nodes2$media[!is.na(nodes2$media.type)])

# when we use the second projection, we select those label belong to the user
# by selection is.na(...)
# thus, an incidence matrix net2 can be represented in two modes
plot(net2.bp$proj2, vertex.label.color="black", vertex.label.dist=1,

     vertex.size=7, vertex.label=nodes2$media[ is.na(nodes2$media.type)])
```
* there is three way to plot a graph accordingly.
    * specify the parameters in the plot() function
    * add the patermeters to the element of the networks
    * use the interactive plot tool (tkplot) to tweat or plot.
    * **NOTICE: the first way will overwrite the settings set by the second way, just like the in-line css will overwrite the embedded stylesheet and the external stylesheet.**
* Network layouts are simply algorithms that return coordinates for each node in a network. We pass the layout function name into the parameter of plot() to define the way we caculate the coordinates of the vertices.
* save the layout as a variable in order to rebirth a satiisfied one. for example, fix the nodes at the same position and generate different pictures for comparison.
* **force-directed algorithms** for layout are the algorithms that simulate and exploit the equilibrium of pratices(node) when those practices interact with its neighbours (such as electrostatic force).
